$$ would I integrate normally and inverse it? like: $$\int\frac{1}{dy} = \frac{1}{y} + c $$

This was a practice problem I was given. Show that $\lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sqrt[n]{a} =1$ . My argument is as follows: \begin{align}
\lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sqrt[n]{a}
&= \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} e^{\ln(\sqrt[n]{a})} \\
&= e^{\lim_{n \rightarrow \infty}(\frac{1}{n}) \ln(a)} \\
&= e^{\lim_{n \rightarrow \infty}(0 \cdot \ln(a))} \\
&= e^0 \\
&= 1.\end{align}
